Brief Hospital Course:
___ year old female HIV, ESRD on HD catheter recently moved here 
from ___ presenting with positive blood cultures from 
dialysis.
.
#Hypotension: No leukocytosis but is immunosuppressed without 
records to be certain of hemodynamic baseline. Borderline tachy, 
borderline hypotensive. Elevated lactate and +BCx but not 
particularly aggressive bacteria. It seems BPs low at baseline 
but sepsis cannot be ruled out but seems low likelihood at this 
time. If sepsis, line most likely source. No urine output at 
baseline but seems to be mentating well with no other have signs 
of end organ dysfunction.  Also possible is hypovolemia with 
recent dialsysis. ___ nephrologist was contacted and baseline 
bps was reported to be SBP 80-90s. Her hypotension was felt to 
be related to large volume loss with recent dialysis. Lactate 
normalized with administration of 500cc NS bolus.  She ambulated 
and did not have any dizziness. 
Per renal, pt will be continued on IV vancomycin for 
coag-negative staph to be dosed per HD protocol. Team did not 
feel that hypotension was related to sepsis however treatemnt of 
positive blood culture was followed and pending blood cultures 
should be monitored/followed up as an ___. Next HD session is 
___ and would recommend reconsideration of small volume 
removal given symptomatic BP with aggressive volume removal.
.
# +Positive BCx: Coag neg staph likely from line. Has no fever 
or leukocytosis. No urine to culture. CXR clear. Serial blood 
cultures obtained and NGTD at time of discharge. Team 
entertained idea of TTE/echo to r/o endocarditis if BCx 
persistently positive however given clinical improvement this 
was not pursued. Plan to continue Vanc for 2 weeks per renal and 
treat through. 
.

provided with medication refills on all meds. Pt states that she 
hasn't have close follow up in many months and was unable to 
identify source for her Rx's - team very concerned for poor HIV 
prognosis given high likelihood of medication non-compliance.
